        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>C.M.<lb/></p>
            <p>Exeter&#44; New Hampshire&#44;<lb/>
                November 17&#44; 1885.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. Mr. S. Morais&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear sir&#58; My good friend&#44;<lb/> Mr. Alfred A. Marcus of Boston&#44;<lb/> again very kindly refers me to you&#44;<lb/> of whom he most complimentarily writes&#58;<lb/> &#34;I consider the most learned literary mean<lb/> in the United States the Rev&#39;d Mr.<lb/> S. Morais of Philadelphia.&#34;¬ù There is<lb/> a matter&#44; my dear Mr. Morais&#44; upon<lb/> which I would very much like to have<lb/> your learned opinion. In regard to a<lb/> published Life of the famed and<lb/> historical King Solomon&#44; regarding<lb/> which I recently addressed a note<lb/> to a most learned friend. In reply<lb/> he kindly wrote&#58; &#34; You inquire if a<lb/> Life of Solomon&#44; properly so called&#44;<lb/> has ever been written. My reply is I<lb/> think not. One would be desirable&#59;<lb/> and I believe that the material and data&#44;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>acknowledged to be reliable&#44; could be<lb/> collected in quantity sufficient to<lb/> make a very interesting volume.<lb/> The accounts that we have of the<lb/> wisest and most foolish of men<lb/> are only the biblical records&#44; made<lb/> up in short biographic form&#44; as in<lb/> Encyclopaedias&#44; dictionaries of biog&#45;<lb/>raphy&#44; &#38; c&#44; with speculations and<lb/> prosings here and there. One will &#94; find<lb/> more written in expansion of Sol&#45;<lb/>omon&#39;s wisdom&#44; in sermons and lec&#45;<lb/>tures than written upon the facts<lb/> of his life and the many traditions<lb/> spread through the East concerning<lb/> him. I would say that what you<lb/> inquire about is still a desideratum.<lb/> Shall I devote five years to it&#44; and<lb/> try to fulfill or supply the want&#63;<lb/> It would be well to collect and col&#45;<lb/>late all the traditions and beliefs<lb/> that exist among the Mohammedan<lb/> nations and others concerning this<lb/> wonderful man&#59; to sift them&#59; by<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>the  rules of historical criticism to<lb/> arrange and establish the true&#44; and&#44;<lb/> if possible&#44; to compile an exhaustive<lb/> work upon the prince of princes.&#34;¬ù<lb/></p> 
            <p>What think you&#44; my dear Mr. Mo&#45;<lb/>rais&#44; of my friend&#39;s project&#44; as he<lb/> briefly outlines it&#63; He is a very<lb/> learned and industrious man of<lb/> the age of sixty or more years. I<lb/> think him abundantly capable<lb/> of performing the work. Is there<lb/> not in the story of Solomon&#39;s life&#44;<lb/> as there is not in that of any other<lb/> man in the whole world&#39;s history&#44;<lb/> much&#44; very much&#44; material<lb/> &#34;To point a moral&#44; or adorn a tale&#34;¬ù&#63;<lb/> Would  not such a work&#44; judiciously<lb/> performed&#44; be a lasting monument<lb/> to the memory of my friend&#63;&#45;&#45;<lb/> no such work ever having been writ&#45;<lb/>ten in all the years since Solomon&#39;s<lb/> time&#44; and when in these later days<lb/> far more than in the Bible times &#40;Ec&#45;<lb/>clesiastes xii&#44; 12&#41; &#34;Of making many<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>books there is no end&#34;¬ù&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>Kindly give me your opinion&#44;<lb/> fully and freely&#44; of my friend&#39;s<lb/> proposed literary work&#44; and I<lb/> will ever remain<lb/></p>
            <p>Gratefully yours&#45;&#45;<lb/>
                Charles Marseilles.<lb/></p>
            </body>
